Tuples

Tuples are arrays with a fixed number of elements where each element has a specific type.

### Basic Tuple

```typescript
let person: [string, number] = ["Alice", 30];

const name: string = person[0]; // "Alice"
const age: number = person[1]; // 30
```

### Tuple with Multiple Types

```typescript
let httpResponse: [number, string, boolean] = [200, "OK", true];

const statusCode: number = httpResponse[0];
const message: string = httpResponse[1];
const success: boolean = httpResponse[2];
```

### Optional Tuple Elements

```typescript
type Coordinates = [number, number, number?];

const point2D: Coordinates = [10, 20];
const point3D: Coordinates = [10, 20, 30];
```

### Rest Elements in Tuples

```typescript
type StringNumbers = [string, ...number[]];

const item: StringNumbers = ["hello", 1, 2, 3];
```

### Labeled Tuples

```typescript
type HttpResponse = [status: number, message: string, data?: unknown];

const response: HttpResponse = [200, "Success", { id: 1 }];
```

### Readonly Tuples

```typescript
const point: readonly [number, number] = [3, 4];
// point[0] = 5; // Error: readonly
```

> **Key Point:** Tuples preserve the order and type of each element, unlike regular arrays.

codeExample:
// Key-value pair tuple
type KeyValue<K, V> = [key: K, value: V];

const entry: KeyValue<string, number> = ["age", 30];

// Tuple destructuring
const [key, value] = entry;
console.log(`${key}: ${value}`); // "age: 30"

// CSV row as tuple
type CsvRow = [id: number, name: string, email: string, active: boolean];

const row: CsvRow = [1, "Alice", "alice@example.com", true];

// Tuple with spread
function merge<T extends any[]>(...args: T): T {
  return args;
}

const merged = merge([1, 2] as const, ["a", "b"] as const);
